english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Yi Gong of Iksan with Preface
  author: Yi Saek
  language: eng
  text: |
    The Yi clan of Iksan has long been renowned. The Left Vice Minister of the Board of Personnel, Yi Ju-yeon, begat Chamberlain Yi Yeol, who begat Historiographer Yi Young-jae, who begat the posthumously titled Left Vice Minister Yi Yang-jin, who begat the Silver-ranked Attendant, Left Vice Minister, and Hanlin Academician Yi Chu. From Academician Yi came Director of the National University Yi Haeng-geom, a man known for his integrity and uprightness.

    When Director Yi served in the Ministry of Justice, his colleagues, pressed by powerful interests, sought to overturn a righteous verdict. Yet the Director refused utterly to yield. Falling ill and taking leave, his colleagues rejoiced at his absence and proceeded with their scheme. But that night, someone dreamed of a keen blade descending from heaven, cleaving the officials in two. Soon after, all those officials died suddenly, while the Director alone remained unharmed—a tale still recounted to this day. The Director begat Chamberlain Yi Aya, who married the daughter of Song Tam, a gentleman of the genteel rank. On the twenty-fourth day of the twelfth month of the Zhiyuan era, Yi Aya fathered our Minister. Yet the mother passed away shortly after his birth, and the child was raised in the household of the Grand Councilor Jeon Sa-ui, his sister's husband. When Councilor Jeon yet lived, the Minister had already risen high, serving him as one serves a father. When Jeon passed, the Minister served his sister as a mother, burying her in the same grave and fulfilling all rites with unwavering devotion even in his old age—truly one who honored his obligations.

    In the Zhiyuan era, Geng-chen year, the Minister was thirty-three. At that time, Lord Kim Yeong-don and Lord An Chuk administered the great examination. The Minister, as Vice Commander and Censor, achieved the highest honors. In the Zhizheng era, Xin-si year, he was twice promoted: to Director of Ceremonial Rank and Lecturer at the National University. In Ren-wu year, he became Esteemed Grand Mentor, Grand Keeper of Rites, and Compiler of Imperial Edicts. In Gui-wei year, he advanced further. In Jia-shen year, he rose to Grand Councillor, Keeper of Rites, Vice Minister of State, and Chief Lecturer of the Imperial Academy. Through the years that followed, his honors multiplied—each promotion reflecting his steadfast virtue and wisdom.

    In Xin-chou year, when bandits invaded our northern reaches, the Minister mounted his horse and rode alone to join the court's retreat into the heartland. The Emperor, greatly pleased, received him with highest honor. The following year, he was appointed Grand Counselor and Minister of Works. When the capital lay ravaged by war and all things needed rebuilding, the Minister came forth. With keen judgment and steady purpose, he guided the realm's recovery. He distributed grain and seed so that idlers vanished from the fields. He upheld the rites at the ancestral temples and supported the schools so that learning flourished. He fostered both martial prowess and refined arts—all with such understanding that later generations could but marvel.

    In Gui-mao year, when the court returned to the capital, treacherous officials schemed to depose the rightful king. The Emperor sent the Minister with solemn memorials to the imperial capital. Arriving at the Western Capital, the Minister bowed before the Imperial Ancestor's tomb and swore: "Should our sovereign fail to be restored, I shall not return to my native land alive." Reaching the capital, the Empress and Imperial Heir sent emissaries without ceasing. On the third day of the fourth month, the Emperor summoned the Minister to the Palace and received him with warmth. The Empress herself hosted a feast, saying, "You have shown utmost devotion to my mother—you are as my own brother. How could I not receive you as such?"

    The Minister replied with eloquence, speaking of the virtuous consorts of ancient Zhou whose wisdom brought forth sage rulers, and of those consorts whose folly brought ruin to dynasties. He spoke of Goryeo's sacred bond with Yuan, formed a hundred years past, asking how the realm could thrive if one man's grudge overshadowed righteousness. His words moved the Empress deeply, yet her displeasure had not fully subsided. She commanded that the Minister return with the Prince.

    The Minister pleaded illness and requested to remain. By imperial decree, all Goryeo officials save the Minister were to depart with the Prince. On the twenty-first day, he was appointed Director of Rites and Ceremonies. The following day, he petitioned the throne, saying, "This old man was born in a distant land. My speech is rough and my knowledge of imperial ritual is slight. How could I presume to serve without drawing ridicule? Moreover, generals without have yet received no reward for their deeds. I fear the realm will judge Your Majesty harshly."

    Though he did not receive the Emperor's consent, the Minister faithfully discharged his duties. At the Grand Sacrifice, serving twice as Chief Rite-Keeper, all who witnessed him were moved to reverence. The Emperor ordered posthumous honors for his forefathers and honor for his parents. His grandmother, mother, and wife were all granted noble rank.

    The Imperial Heir summoned the Minister to Mount Longevity, to the Palace of Broad Cold. There, the Heir asked the meaning of the characters "Benevolence" and "Wisdom" inscribed above. The Minister replied, "Benevolence is loving the people; Wisdom is discerning all things. Should an emperor wield these two virtues in governing the realm, ten thousand generations shall know peace." Within the palace, gazing upon pillars of gold and jade, the Heir inquired, "Has an old man such as yourself ever seen pillars like these?" The Minister answered, "I have heard that when a sage ruler governs justly, even a humble wooden dwelling becomes as firm as gold and jade. But should he fail in virtue, even the hardest stone turns to rot."

    The Heir set down a lute mid-song, saying, "Long unused, I have forgotten how to play." The Minister knelt and replied, "Should you never forget the heart that grieves for your people, what matter if a melody or two upon the strings escape your memory?" When the Emperor, sailing upon the great lake, heard these words through the Heir's report, he exclaimed, "Indeed, I knew this old man to be virtuous. Among all your mother's kinfolk, he alone remains."

    Once the Empress asked why her brother's household had fallen to ruin. The Minister replied, "Greed breeds resentment, and from resentment springs calamity. The times themselves pressed hard upon him—it was no fault of the king."

    Yet palace eunuchs whispered poison into the Empress's ear, and the Minister found himself forgotten. When the Prince departed for distant lands, treacherous ministers schemed to seize the Minister and bear him away. Learning of their plot, the Minister told his secretary, "I have no parents, no heirs, and have risen to the highest station. What further concern have I for this world? I shall shave my head and ascend the mountains. I shall not yield to them."

    When the conspirators petitioned the Emperor, he refused their plea. In autumn, a great general arose and purged the traitors from court, restoring the rightful king to his throne. The Minister, seeking only peace, departed through the city gates, commanding his servant to play the flute. "Is there joy in this world greater than this?" he asked. Along the road, when his servant purchased grain for the tired horse with an arrow—robbing a poor farmer—the Minister cut cloth from his own robe to pay the true price. At an empty station where grain lay scattered in the fields, he inquired the fair exchange, wrote it upon scraps, and left payment within the pile. When his servant protested, "The horse-keeper will simply take it back," the Minister replied, "I know this well. Yet only thus can my heart find peace."

    Returning to the capital, the Minister gave the golden belt bestowed by the Emperor to aid in reconstructing the National University. Though powerful men now viewed him with suspicion, he retreated into quiet virtue, remaining at home unseen.

    There, in the fourth month, he was appointed Left Minister of the Metropolitan Council and Minister of Military Records. The following year, in the tenth month, he was advanced to Grand Councillor, Keeper of Rites, and Chief Lecturer—positions of great honor. Yet in all this, he never once sat in the council halls to exercise the duties of Chief Minister, which many regarded as cause for sorrow.

    Alas, the Minister's brilliance and prudence were unmatched among the elders of his age. His decisiveness and uprightness bent to no man's will, yet beneath flowed a grace both refined and serene, a love of mountain and stream he could not fully conceal. He built a hermitage in De-soo County, calling himself Master of the Southern Village. In silk cap and walking staff, he gathered friends from his youth and spent his days in whispered song and verse. When students came to pay their respects, he sent them away drunk with wine.

    His wife, the lady Kim, was descended thirteen generations from the Great King Kim of Silla and was the daughter of the Great Minister Kim Sang-gi. Of virtuous character, she was worthy of her husband, and all the clan praised her kindness.

    In the bing-wu year, in the fifth month, the Minister fell gravely ill. Learning of his passing, the king granted him the posthumous name "Loyal and Righteous" and ordered the state to bear all funeral expenses. He was buried at the foot of the western hill near his hermitage.

    Having no son, he raised the daughter of a kinsman and gave her in marriage to An Suk, a scholar of the National University. The Yi clan, through eight generations to the Minister, had ever grown in brilliance. The virtue of his ancestor the Director of the University bore fruit in the Minister's life, and through him the family's glory shone yet brighter. Yet with no heir to continue the line, one perceives how all beings are but shadows passing through an empty sky.

    The Minister's courtesy name was omitted from the records. His residence was called the Pavilion of Equilibrium. When the Minister journeyed to offer congratulations on the imperial birthday, I accompanied him. I received my education at the National University and, through the civil examination, rose to office—all through his grace and favor. How could I refuse to inscribe his epitaph?

    Thus I write:

    Through three winters the green pine holds its straightness.
    A hundred times the iron is forged to strength.

    Wondrous was Minister Loyal-and-Righteous,
    Moving through court with flowing ease—
    A spring cool and clear,
    A wind soft and fragrant.

    He gave all his heart to his sovereign,
    And the Emperor praised his resolve.
    Reaping no glory for himself,
    All men revered his righteousness.

    He joined the great sacrifice,
    And all affirmed its auspiciousness.
    Not the measure of his deeds,
    But the unity of his virtue—

    Though he left no sons to continue his line,
    The ancestral shrine remains preserved.
